= 5 |nationalgoals4 = 0 |nationalyears5 = 2018 |nationalteam5 = [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] |nationalcaps5 = 3 |nationalgoals5 = 0 |club-update = 23:05, 2 March 2019 (UTC) |nationalteam-update = 23:05, 2 March 2019 (UTC) }} '''Declan Rice''' (born 14 January 1999) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre back]] or [[defensive midfielder]] for {{English football updater|WestHamU}} club [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].
==Club career== ===Youth=== Rice was born and raised in [[Kingston upon Thames]], London.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/sport/soccer/soccer-news/declan-rice-looks-good-friend-12214311 |title=Declan Rice looks to good friend John Terry for guidance as he readies for Ireland debut |first=Paul |last=O'Hehir |website=Irish Mirror |publisher=Reach |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>{{better source|date=February 2019}} His paternal grandparents were from [[Douglas, County Cork|Douglas]], County Cork.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/international-soccer/declan-rice-theres-no-decision-to-be-made-if-i-didnt-want-to-be-playing-for-ireland-i-wouldnt-be-here-36723118.html |title=Declan Rice: 'There's no decision to be made. If I didn't want to be playing for Ireland, I wouldn't be here' |first=Daniel |last=McDonnell |newspaper=Irish Independent |location=Dublin |date=20 March 2018 |accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> He grew up in [[Kingston upon Thames]] and joined the [[Chelsea F.C. Under-23s and Academy|academy]] of [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in 2006, as a seven-year-old.<ref>{{Cite news |title=West Ham's Declan Rice on his rapid rise and future plans with club and country |first=Matthew |last=Nash |newspaper=Metro |location=London |date=9 November 2018 |accessdate=10 November 2018 |url=https://www.metro.news/west-hams-declan-rice-on-his-rapid-rise-and-future-plans-with-club-and-country/1302609/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ireland anger over England's move for Declan Rice |last=Northcroft |first=Jonathan |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=2 September 2018 |accessdate=7 September 2018 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ireland-anger-over-englands-move-for-declan-rice-zsgt6b05f|url-access=limited}}</ref> In 2014, after his release at the age of 14, he joined the [[West Ham United F.C. Under-23s and Academy|academy]] of [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rice proud to prove a point to Chelsea after being released |first=Ken |last=Dyer |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=9 April 2018 |accessdate=7 September 2018 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/west-hams-declan-rice-proud-to-prove-a-point-to-chelsea-after-being-released-a3809361.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Declan Rice says no to West Ham United deal |last1=Hirst |first1=Paul |last2=Joyce |first2=Paul |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=7 June 2018 |accessdate=7 September 2018 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/declan-rice-says-no-to-west-ham-united-deal-mgs3vx0d0}}</ref>
===West Ham United=== On 16 December 2015, just over a year after joining West Ham United at youth level, Rice signed his first professional contract with the club.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/december/28-december/declan-rice-career-timeline |title=Declan Rice: A career timeline |date=28 December 2018 |accessdate=28 December 2018 |publisher=West Ham United F.C.}}</ref> Rice was called into the West Ham senior squad for the first time for the games against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in April 2017, after impressing in the [[West Ham United F.C. Under-23s and Academy|under-23 team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/players/exclusive-declan-rice-says-stay-13007172 |title=EXCLUSIVE: Declan Rice says he will stay level headed despite West Ham call-up |first=Sam |last=Inkersole |website=football.london |date=9 May 2017 |accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref> He made his senior debut against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on the last day of the [[2016–17 Premier League]] season, coming on as a 91st-minute substitute for [[Edimilson Fernandes]] in a 2–1 away win,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39912028 |title=Burnley 1–2 West Ham United |date=21 May 2017 |accessdate=21 May 2017 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2017/may/22-may/rice-its-dream-come-true |title=Rice&nbsp;– It's a dream come true |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref> five days after captaining the under-23's to promotion with a 2–1 win at [[Newcastle United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Newcastle United]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whufc.com/fixtures/first-team/fixtures-and-results/season-20162017/newcastle-united-vs-west-ham-united-1 |title=Newcastle United v West Ham United |date=16 May 2017 |accessdate=18 August 2017 |publisher=West Ham United F.C.}}</ref> His full senior debut came on 19 August 2017 in a 3–2 defeat at [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/fixtures-results/revealed-declan-rice-starts-west-13500341 |title=Revealed:Rice starts for West Ham against Southampton and Antonio returns |first=Sam |last=Inkersole |website=football.london |date=19 August 2017 |accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref>
In April 2018, Rice was named as runner-up for the 2017–18 [[West Ham United F.C.#Hammer of the Year|Hammer of the Year]] award behind [[Marko Arnautović]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/april/25-april/arnautovic-crowned-betway-hammer-year |title=Arnautovic crowned Betway Hammer of the Year |publisher=West Ham United F.C.}}</ref> On 22 December, he made his 50th appearance for West Ham, the first player to do so while still a teenager since [[Michael Carrick]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Mason's ironic cheers & Rice going mad – West Ham moments missed |last=Inkersole |first=Sam |website=football.london |date=15 November 2018 |accessdate=30 December 2018 |url=https://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/fixtures-results/masons-ironic-cheers-holebass-clearance-15588611}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Analysis: Resilient Rice has shown age is no barrier |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |date=29 December 2018 |accessdate=30 December 2018 |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/december/29-december/analysis-resilient-rice-has-shown-age-no-barrier}}</ref> On 28 December, Rice signed a new contract until 2024 with the option of an additional year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/december/28-december/west-ham-united-sign-declan-rice-new-long-term-contract |title=West Ham United sign Declan Rice to new long-term contract |publisher=West Ham United F.C. |accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref> Rice scored his first goal for West Ham, and was named [[man of the match]], in a 1–0 win against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 12 January 2019 in West Ham's 50th Premier League game at the [[London Stadium]].<ref>{{cite new |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46766896 |title=West Ham United 1–0 Arsenal |first=Neil |last=Johnston |date=12 January 2019 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>
==International career== Although born in London, Rice is eligible to play for Ireland as his grandparents were from [[Cork (city)|Cork]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/international-soccer/rice-grateful-to-talent-scout-otoole-for-helping-his-swift-rise-36198526.html |title=Rice grateful to talent scout O'Toole for helping his swift rise |first=John |last=Fallon |newspaper=Irish Independent |location=Dublin |date=5 October 2017 |accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> On 19 March 2017, Rice was named [[Republic of Ireland national under-17 football team|Republic of Ireland U17]] player of the year.<ref name="3fai2">{{cite web |url=http://www.fai.ie/ireland/news/winners-revealed-for-three-fai-international-football-awards |title=Winners revealed for Three FAI International Football Awards |publisher=Football Association of Ireland |accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref> On 23 May 2017, only days after his [[Premier League]] debut, Rice was named in the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] squad to play friendlies against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] and [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] and a World Cup qualifier at home to [[Austria national football team|Austria]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/international-soccer/west-ham-teenager-declan-rice-called-into-ireland-senior-squad-by-martin-oneill-along-with-cork-duo-35747101.html |title=West Ham teenager Declan Rice called into Ireland senior squad by Martin O'Neill along with Cork duo |first=Aidan |last=Fitzmaurice |newspaper=Irish Independent |location=Dublin |date=23 May 2017 |accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref> He made his senior debut on 23 March 2018 in a 1–0 defeat to [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.the42.ie/ireland-turkey-report-3921212-Mar2018/ |title=New faces fail to inspire Ireland in Turkey |date=23 March 2018 |website=The42.ie |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>
In August 2018, Rice was omitted from the squad to play [[Wales national football team|Wales]] by manager [[Martin O'Neill]] who said that Rice was considering switching to play for [[England national football team|England]] after being approached by them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/27/england-have-spoken-to-declan-rice-martin-oneill-west-ham |title=England 'have spoken to' West Ham's Declan Rice, says Martin O'Neill |agency=Press Association |date=27 August 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref> By November 2018, having been omitted from three squads selected by O'Neill, Rice said he was no closer in deciding whether to play for Ireland or England.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46153251 |title=Declan Rice: Choosing between England and Republic of Ireland not easy |date=9 November 2018 |accessdate=10 November 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In December 2018, Rice met with new Ireland manager [[Mick McCarthy]] and his assistant, [[Robbie Keane]]. McCarthy said that Rice was a potential future captain of Ireland and that he would build the team around Rice should he decide to play for the country.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46666804 |title=Declan Rice: Republic of Ireland boss Mick McCarthy says West Ham player could be his captain |date=23 December 2018 |accessdate=28 December 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 13 February 2019, Rice pledged his future to England.<ref> {{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/declan-rice-england-republic-of-ireland-country-nationality-west-ham-united-gareth-southgate-a8777776.html |title=Declan Rice pledges future to England |date=13 February 2019 |accessdate= 13 February 2019 |publisher=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47286157|title=Declan Rice: Is West Ham midfielder ready for England?|date=18 February 2019|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>
